content.description: Start below a slightly angling off-fingers splitter about 20' up. First couple moves are easy but on a layer of poor quality rock, start a couple feet to the right and then traverse left a bit to get to the good sandstone and up to the crack. Ring-lock and/or layback up the off-fingers splitter to a small pod at a sloping horizontal shelf, then enjoy the thin hands crack up to bolt anchors.
content.protection: Takes a decent variety of sizes, heavier on the #0.75 and #1 camalots.
content.location: Approx 200' left of Elation/Evacuation

climbs.name: Unnamed (#11 in new Creek Freak guide)

content.description:
At the time I wrote Creek Freak, I did not climb this route nor did I find anyone that had. Just climbed this awkward route 3/2019.

The route starts with a "ground leaving crux" to establish yourself in a wedge/flare. Climb the flare to a narrow shallow chimney with a thin fingers crack in it. At the top of said chimney the second crux is passed by exiting the chimney to a shallow right facing corner. Climb the less than vertical corner with fingers to a 2 bolt anchor on the right wall.
content.protection: Green Alien - .05 Camelot
content.location: From the top of the trail walk left. Just before the route (Calibration 5.9) there is a juniper tree very close to the cliff. The start of this route is literally behind the juniper.

content.description: A nice big hands crack in a corner with numerous small ledges on the right wall for hands and feet if you would prefer.  The rock at the top gets a little soft and loose but most of the route is solid.  A 70m rope just reaches but probably best to tie a knot in the end of your rope.
content.protection: About 5 or 6 #3 Camalot and 2 or 3 #3 Friends.  2 #1 Camalots and 1 each .5, .75 & #5. Two bolt anchor at the top with webbing.
content.location: Far right side of Bioturbation wall, on the left side of a tower formation.

content.description: Atypical creek climbing.  Book calls it 5.12.  Get up on a ledge, clip a bolt.  Pull bouldery moves, clip another bolt, more liebacking then reach for the first tips lock.  Finger cams after that... there is a third bolt up higher too.  My partners thought it was easier than 12- but they're really strong.  I thought it's 11+ / 12-.
content.protection: 3 draws, anchor draws, finger pieces up to maybe #1 camalot
content.location: Right of Chest Full of Kind and Cups.  Right under the anchors for Lifer.

content.description: The book calls this a stellar route and I agree.  Lots of #1 camalots.  Go up a corner then make your way out the long left traverse roof.  Just keep moving!
content.protection: lots of #1s a couple of .75s, maybe a #4 for the start, and few #2 camalots.
content.location: a ways right of Chest Full of Kind and Cups.  Look for the corner to the roof that goes left.  Slightly left of directly beneath the anchors is Scrunch.

content.description: Junky easy jams lead to finger locks and tips with a subtle offset. Fight the barn door as the crack curves right and eases up.  Five bolts are obvious and lead through odd and sustained arete wrestling. It's possible to move right into the crack system above Elation and still clip a bolt or two.
content.protection: Doubles in BD 0.2-0.75. Perhaps a single 0.1 and 1. Five draws for the bolts plus anchor gear.
content.location: About 200 ft right of where the approach trail hits the cliff. Look for a right-curving chalked up thin crack leading to a bolted arete. Two 5.10 looking climbs - JackOLation and Elation - are on either side of the arete.

content.description:
This left-facing dihedral of excellent varnish varies between fingers and thin-hands with some face features until about 2/3 height, then it pinches down to less than tips, but has flared pods and face features that allow for strenuous laybacking/stemming to a good lock or crimp stance at the chains.

The gear is small and fiddly up top, but the rock is very good and there's good gear a short way below. Punch it!
content.protection:
(3)green C3s (2) .3-.75 (1)#1, #3---BD sizes

Chain/cold shut anchor
content.location: About 1/2 way between the prow where the south face meets the west face and the Bioturbation route on the southern aspect. There's a plaque. This is listed as To Be Determined 5.11 in the new Creek guide.

content.description: Start off with off fingers to tight hands with good feet. Continue up through a small roof before the angle eases and it widens to hands.
content.protection: 3-4 each of C4 reds and yellows. Optional 3 high and 0.75 low.
content.location: The easiest route to locate is Lee-Tardation, a right curving tips crack to a bolted arete immediately left of Elation, and perhaps a couple hundred feet right of where the trail hits the cliff. Jack-O-Lation is a left facing corner about 10 ft left with a slightly higher start.

content.description: Hard stemming and palming crux with small gear leads to much more moderate laybacking in some questionable rock.
content.protection: small nuts-BD#3
content.location: Towards the right end of the wall in between Elation and Laceration.

content.description: A right facing corner with a finger splitter on the left wall and a crack in the corner.  Climb using both cracks till the left one gets to small and then continue up the corner crack with some hands sizes through a mini roof.
content.protection: .3 to #3 Camalots
content.location: About a 100' left of Bioturbation, just left of Evacuation.

content.description: Mostly fun tight fingers in a right-facing corner. Climb ten feet up to a bolt then transfer into the corner.
content.protection: .3 - #3. (Decent amount of .4s). One draw. 2 bolt anchor.
content.location: Middle of Bioturbation on the west side. Not too far left of where the approach trail meets the wall. Plaque.

content.description: start up a section of sandy rock to gain the left facing corner. hands leads to a wider section that can be laybacked then to perfect cups for the remainder of the route.
content.protection: #2, 3, and 4 camalots. heavy on the 3's.
content.location: about 200ft right of chest full of kind. look for a nice left facing corner with dark lickeny rock. doesn't get climbed very much, but the anchors are new.

content.description:
The leftmost climb on the Bioturbation Wall and well left of all the other climbs - more easily approached from Way Rambo.  Chest Full of Kind takes the right side of the obvious arch (visible from the road).

Steep & pumpy, but short.
content.protection: Mostly hands.

climbs.name: Chalking Up Rails
climbs.fa: Trevor Bowman, Pat Kingsbury, Ty Gittins 2/22/13

content.description: Shallow changing corners with fingers/tight-hands end with crux moves out of the crack where it pinches down to less than tips, one long reach hits the first of a series of surprising crimps that quickly turn to large flat rails as the angle rolls over. Uncharacteristic face climbing for the Creek along the now very thin crack. Unless you bring several 000 C3s, this final bit will be runout, but it's pretty mellow climbing.
content.protection:
(2)#1 (1)#.75, #.5 (3)#.4 (2)#.3, gray #000 C3

Chain/cold shut anchor
content.location: On the far right side of the wall. 20' right of Biomass, which is plaqued.

content.description: A short OW to invert roof, ends at "Chalking up Rails" anchor
content.protection: 4s and 5s, plus a black alien
content.location: Between Chalking and Crunch

content.description: This one is on somewhat softer rock, with a bit of looseness in the OW--keep a heads up! Fists to a stembox with a blocky OW into cleaner tight-hands and hands and finally a shallow stembox with a tips-fist crack.
content.location: Currently the furthest right known route on the wall. About 15' right of Chalking up Rails.

climbs.name: Bruce Lee as FUCK
climbs.fa: FA: Patrick Kingsbury, Jessica Kilroy, David Elder

content.description:
Amazing thin hands splitter near a corner to immaculate splitter offwidth to fists through a huge roof, finishes with more ow above the roof.

Watch Fists of Fury, you'll get the idea
content.protection: Single .4 .5 .75; 3x 1's; single 2 and 3; 3x new 4; 2x 5 friends; 2x old 4's; 2 new 5's
content.location: Just right of Lifer and Regime Change

content.description: Fingers to off fingers to .75 to thin hands to hands in a right-facing corner.  Lieback if you want but the crack is good enough to jam.
content.protection: 1 green alien, 2 yellow, 2 .5 camalot, 3 - 4x .75 camalot, 2 x #1, 1x #2.  #2 friends might be better for the middle section.
content.location: faces up-canyon kinda in the direction that way rambo faces.  far right side of bioturbation wall.  from way rambo parking, head down the road a little then make your way up to the wall.  we didn't find any good trail.

content.description: A beautiful, clean OW-squeeze in a left-facing dihedral. Brief crux over the bulge at 25'.
content.protection: (2)#3-#5 (3)#6--BD sizes chain/cold shut anchor
content.location: On the far right side of the wall. No established path on the last bit.

content.description: Crack starts with fingers and as it turns to off-width, face holds ease the difficulty.
content.location: From the approach trail head left until you reach a small sandy looking pillar.

content.description: Where you park for Way Rambo Wall is essentially the same jumping off point for this wall.  300 yards prior to hitting the gate at the end of the road, head uphill past some cool looking rock mushrooms to the base of the wall.  Wander right until you run into some plaques at the base of several climbs.  Alienation is located in a right-facing dihedral with a blocky start.  A 7'x7' square boulder resides at the base.  From the base you can see the wide crack start 25' up (4.5") and the perfect handcrack finish about 80' up.  The wide bit is very positive with decent feet and narrows down the higher you go.  Awesome fist jams take you to the base of the handcrack.  Perfect hands to the camoflauged two bolt anchor.  It's a worthy moderate route.
content.protection: Green, Yellow & Red Aliens. Camalots; 2 each(.75)&(#1), 3 each(#2) 1 each: (#3), (#3.5),(#4),(#4.5)

content.description: Some very cool face climbing on good rock (11-ish) past two bolts get one into the left-facing dihedral, which runs from hands to tips with some very tough stemming/face climbing at the top where the crack seams up. Everything below the crux is excellent on this, but the awkward finish on crunchier rock detracts from it.
content.protection:
2 bolts, fixed stopper, (1)#1-#.4 (3).3 (2)green C3s

Chain/cold shut anchor.
content.location: About 100' or so left of Bioturbation. Plaqued.

content.description: Start up the low angle crack in a right facing corner, then climb the flake until it thins out into a seem.  Traverse left about 5ft to the fun part, pull over the bulge on fingers continue this for a few more moves to the anchor.
content.protection: Double rack from 3's - .3's (B.D.)
content.location: Between Alienation & Bioturbation.  Two bolts W/T webbing & a mallion I placed 8/30/17.
